## 2. Training

### 2.1 Standard run (full trajectories)

```bash
python NEXT_training_mo_cl_ref_loss_new_agent_grdth_heun.py \
    --tgt-data-paths trajectory_library/phases/HighE_HGV \
    --sr 100000000 \
    --use-scalar \
    --aug 0 \
    --nhidden 200 \
    -o model_outputs/SBI/GRUODE_run/GEODESIC/glide \
    --frame geodesic \
    --geodesic-mode integrated \
    --model-type gruode \
    --sbi-phase glide \
    --dt 1
```

### 2.2 Sliding-window training (recommended — see §6)

Add `--window-size` and `--window-stride`:

```bash
python NEXT_training_mo_cl_ref_loss_new_agent_grdth_heun.py \
    ... (same args as above) ... \
    --dt 1 \
    --window-size 60 \
    --window-stride 10
```

- `--window-size N` — train on fixed-length windows of `N` states instead of
  full trajectories. `0` (default) disables windows. For a 300 s glide at
  `--dt 1`, `60` is a reasonable start.
- `--window-stride S` — stride between windows (default `10`).

**What windows do:** uniform-length windows produce **padding-free** batches
(no valid-mask edge cases, no temporal-ramp-over-padding distortion), give
**dense** coverage of every flight condition, and fit the field as *local
dynamics everywhere* — which matches how the simulator deploys it (re-launched
every second from measured states).

Notes:
- Window training automatically disables the random-offset segment augmentation
  (`AUGMENT_SEGMENTS`) so you don't double-augment.
- The model filename gains a `_{N}win_{S}stride` token so windowed models are
  distinguishable from full-trajectory ones.
- **`val_pos_err` with windows is measured over `N`-second horizons**, so it
  reads much lower than full-trajectory runs *by construction*. Do not compare
  it directly to previous full-horizon numbers — use the **simulator** as the
  cross-run yardstick.

### 2.3 Output of a training run

In the output directory you get, among other files:

- `NEXT_..._scalarOn[...].pt` — the checkpoint (weights).
- `NEXT_..._scalarOn[...].onnx` — the field graph.
- `NEXT_..._scalarOn[...]_encoder.onnx` — the encoder graph.
- `NEXT_..._scalarOn[...]_scalar.pickle` — the fitted scaler.

If a training run completed **before** the encoder-export was added, the
`_encoder.onnx` will be missing — use the standalone exporter (§3) to
regenerate both graphs from the `.pt` without retraining.

