## 3. Export (re-generate ONNX from an existing checkpoint)

Use this when you already have a `.pt` but need the ONNX graphs (or need to
regenerate them, e.g. after an export-code fix). **No retraining occurs** — it
loads the weights and writes graphs in seconds.

```bash
python export_gruode_onnx.py \
    --checkpoint model_outputs/SBI/GRUODE_run/GEODESIC/glide/HighE_HGV/NEXT_..._scalarOn.pt \
    --scaler    model_outputs/SBI/GRUODE_run/GEODESIC/glide/HighE_HGV/NEXT_..._scalarOn_scalar.pickle \
    --training-module NEXT_training_mo_cl_ref_loss_new_agent_grdth_heun
```

- `--checkpoint` — path to the trained `.pt`.
- `--scaler` — the scaler pickle from the same run (recommended; populates the
  second-order scaled-space buffers exactly as training did).
- `--training-module` — importable name of your training script (no `.py`), so
  the exporter reuses your exact model classes.

**The script derives the architecture from the checkpoint tensors** (state
size, latent width, encoder input indices) rather than guessing, and refuses to
export if the weights do not load cleanly. A successful run prints:

```
[info] derived from checkpoint: model_states=5, latent_dim=100, enc_in=5, ...
[ok] trained weights loaded cleanly
[ok] wrote field graph:   ...scalarOn.onnx
[ok] wrote encoder graph: ...scalarOn_encoder.onnx
[ok] self-check passed: encoder h0 width=100, field output width=105
```

It writes the field `.onnx` (overwriting any existing one of the same name) and
the `_encoder.onnx` beside it.

